Build Gate Proviso:
- Never render or expose spreadsheet letter identifiers in generated content or public-facing pages.
- Always use semantic entity names (for example, `Intervention Dominance`, `Coverage Timing`, `Evidence Type`).
- Treat any letter-identifier wording in generated outputs as a validation failure that must be fixed before build.

When creating or editing Functional Mechanism (FM) pages:

Follow:
system/functional-mechanism-schema.md

Structure:
- All sections must be present in the exact order defined in the schema
- FM section headings must be explicitly numbered (`## 1. ...`, `## 2. ...`) for PM/FM consistency
- Section contract must include:
  - Definition
  - Functional Role
  - Underlying Mechanisms and Requirements
  - Dietary Levers
  - Lifestyle Levers
  - Scoreable Food-State Inputs
  - Recipe Translation & Scoring Logic
  - Functional Consequences
  - Practical Interpretation
  - Cross-System Links
  - Mechanism Summary Table
  - Scoring Interpretation
  - Interpretation Boundary
  - Evidence Base
  - References
  - Missing Entities (only when needed)

Field interpretation:
- Front matter must use schema field names (`title`, `fm_id`, `parent_brs`, `summary`, `mechanisms_covered`, `key_constraints`, `intervention_dominance`, `coverage_timing`, `references`)
- Underlying mechanisms and requirements must be interpreted as:
  - PMs (Primary Mechanisms) that define the FM
  - KCs (Key Constraints) (substrate/precursor requirements)
  - Cross-BRS links
- Under `3. Underlying Mechanisms and Requirements`, render subsection labels exactly as:
  - `PMs (Primary Mechanisms)`
  - `KCs (Key Constraints)`
- Must not use underlying mechanisms and requirements as a dependency graph
- For BRS6(FM1), PM1 naming must be:
  - Glycaemic Variability & Absorption Kinetics
  - (not legacy Glycaemic Excursion Control)

Scoreable input rules:
- Dietary and Lifestyle rules:
  - `Dietary Levers` and `Lifestyle Levers` must be separate top-level sections
  - `Dietary Levers` must appear immediately after `3. Underlying Mechanisms and Requirements`
  - Diet and Lifestyle content should be wrapped in collapsible `<details>` menus for readability
- Scoreable Food-State Inputs must include all four categories:
  - Functional Property Potentials
  - Realised Functional States
  - Substance / Nutrient Signals
  - Preparation Transformations
- Recipe Translation & Scoring Logic must stay narrative and mechanism-facing
- Do not expose raw scoring code

Diet rules:
- Foods must be derived from:
  - KCs (substrates)
  - PM-linked substances
- All foods must be mechanistically justified
- Must not include generic or "healthy food" lists

Constraints:
- Must not introduce new PMs, FMs, or KCs
- Must not include scoring formulas
- Must not expose raw scoring code
- Must not include SMs during initial rollout
- Must not model one FM as structurally dependent on another
- Must include Interpretation Boundary language clarifying mechanistic/educational scope and non-predictive clinical scope
- Must not display PM/FM codes in recipe-facing examples beyond mechanism-page context

References:
- Use numeric citations [1], [2]
- All references must link to:
  /docs/papers/BRAIN-Diet-References#citationKey
- Verify citationKey exists in static/bibtex/BRAIN-diet.bib
- If a modulator or lifestyle factor is introduced, add evidence-backed inline citations and include matching bibliography references
- Bibliography entries for cited evidence must include DOI or source URL so users can click through to the original source
- If missing, flag: "Missing bibliography entry"

If ambiguity exists, stop and ask.
